**1. DYNAMIC AUTO-SCALING --- CORE ALGORITHM**

**1.1 When Does the Calculator Re-Scale?**

The scaling engine triggers automatically on any of these conditions:

-   S0 sends a new t/h value for EFB, OPDC, or POS (any change from
    previous value)

-   User manually edits a throughput field in the S1 calculator UI

-   A new machine is added to the Supabase equipment_catalogue by the
    user

-   User selects a different OEM/model for any equipment type

-   Scheduled 3-day AI search (Prompt 8) returns updated nameplate
    capacity data

-   Lab result changes POS Fe band → triggers POS inclusion rate change
    → recalculate POS line

**1.2 Scaling Decision Tree**

The following algorithm executes independently for EACH equipment type
in EACH processing line on every trigger:

> ── INPUTS
> ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
>
> stream_tph → fresh weight t/h from S0 for this stream
>
> nameplate_tph → OEM nameplate capacity (from equipment_catalogue)
>
> oem_origin → \'Asian\' \| \'EU\' \| \'Japanese\' \| \'ID-Fabricated\'
>
> ── STEP 1: DERATE
> ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
>
> if oem_origin IN (\'Asian\', \'ID-Fabricated\') → derated_tph =
> nameplate × 0.65
>
> if oem_origin IN (\'EU\', \'Japanese\') → derated_tph = nameplate ×
> 0.85
>
> ── STEP 2: DUTY UNITS
> ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
>
> duty_units = CEIL(stream_tph / derated_tph)
>
> ── STEP 3: UTILISATION CHECK
> ───────────────────────────────────────────
>
> util_pct = (stream_tph / (duty_units × derated_tph)) × 100
>
> if util_pct \> 85% → RED flag, increment duty_units by 1, re-run step
> 3
>
> if util_pct 81-85% → AMBER flag, show comparison table with +1 unit
> option
>
> if util_pct ≤ 80% → GREEN, healthy headroom, proceed
>
> ── STEP 4: BACKUP RULE (IMMUTABLE)
> ─────────────────────────────────────
>
> backup_required = TRUE if motor_kw \> 11
>
> TRUE if equipment_type IN (\'press\',\'shredder\',\'mill\',
>
> \'trommel\',\'decanter\',\'screen\')
>
> FALSE otherwise (conveyors \<11 kW, magnets)
>
> backup_units = 1 if backup_required else 0
>
> total_units = duty_units + backup_units
>
> ── STEP 5: OUTPUT TO DOWNSTREAM CALCULATORS
> ─────────────────────────────
>
> {
>
> tag, equipment_name, duty_units, backup_units, total_units,
>
> nameplate_tph, derated_tph, util_pct, traffic_light,
>
> motor_kw_per_unit, total_kw, footprint_L_m, footprint_W_m,
>
> unit_cost_usd, total_cost_usd, oem, model, lead_time_wk
>
> }

**1.3 Scaling Example --- EFB Increases from 25 t/h to 50 t/h**

When S0 sends EFB = 50 t/h, the algorithm recalculates every machine in
the EFB line:

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Equipment**   **Nameplate   **Derated   **@ 25 t/h **@ 50 t/h **Util %  **Flag**
                  t/h**         (65%)**     (old)**    (new)**    \@50**    
  --------------- ------------- ----------- ---------- ---------- --------- ----------
  Trommel         20            13.0        2 duty + 1 4 duty + 1 96.2% →   RED → 5
  (TR-2601)                                 bkp        bkp        +1 unit   duty

  Screw Press (CB 22            14.3        2 duty + 1 4 duty + 1 87.4% →   AMBER → 5
  20T/C)                                    bkp        bkp        +1 unit   duty

  Shredder        10            6.5         4 duty + 1 8 duty + 1 96.2% →   RED → 10
  (KH-777)                                  bkp        bkp        +1 unit   duty

  Hammer Mill     8             5.2         5 duty + 1 10 duty +  96.2% →   RED → 12
  (YTH-7.100)                               bkp        1 bkp      +1 unit   duty

  Vibratory       11            7.15        4 duty + 1 7 duty + 1 99.7% →   RED → 8
  Screen (SWECO)                            bkp        bkp        +1 unit   duty
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

*After recalculation: CALC-A updates equipment register → CALC-B
recalculates footprint → CALC-C resizes building bays → CALC-D/E
recompute costs → CALC-F/G regenerate drawings. All in one automated
chain.*

